{"version":1,"kind":"Article","sha256":"31c0263f5d7474427027b033d5ee912f177b573d218e15540ec686d31c397c72","slug":"blog.2018.devopsdays-sv-2018","location":"/blog/2018/devopsdays-sv-2018.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"An academic scientist goes to DevOps Days","tags":["python","open science","devops","jupyterhub","teams"],"date":"2018-05-18","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"id":"chris","nameParsed":{"literal":"Chris Holdgraf","given":"Chris","family":"Holdgraf"},"name":"Chris Holdgraf","orcid":"0000-0002-2391-0678","affiliations":["affiliations-myst-generated-uid-0","affiliations-myst-generated-uid-1"],"twitter":"choldgraf","github":"choldgraf","url":"https://chrisholdgraf.com"}],"github":"https://github.com/choldgraf/choldgraf.github.io","affiliations":[{"name":"2i2c","url":"https://2i2c.org","id":"affiliations-myst-generated-uid-0"},{"name":"Project Jupyter","url":"https://jupyter.org","id":"affiliations-myst-generated-uid-1"}],"abbreviations":{"LF":"The Linux Foundation","JF":"The Jupyter Foundation","JEC":"Jupyter Executive Council","JFB":"The Jupyter Foundation Board","SSC":"Software Steering Council","OSPO":"Open Source Program Office"},"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"edit_url":"https://github.com/choldgraf/choldgraf.github.io/blob/main/blog/2018/devopsdays-sv-2018.md","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"devopsdays-sv-2018.md","url":"/build/devopsdays-sv-2018-2fc6188cee713c5eb65a9f419ef90a7b.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Last week I took a few days to attend ","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"key":"cJVbwk8gNc"},{"type":"link","url":"https://www.devopsdays.org/events/2018-silicon-valley/program/","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"DevOpsDays Silicon Valley","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"key":"YAXOS4XZSM"}],"urlSource":"https://www.devopsdays.org/events/2018-silicon-valley/program/","key":"jkd1Vrx3pn"},{"type":"text","value":". My goal\nwas to learn a bit about how the DevOps culture works, what are the things\npeople are excited about and discuss in this community. I’m also interested in\nlearning a thing or two that could be brought back into the scientific / academic world.\nHere are a couple of thoughts from the experience.","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"key":"hGmORtgrN0"}],"key":"FnRCD9jAz2"},{"type":"blockquote","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"tl;dr","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"key":"Vs5QDrSlwO"}],"key":"a6hAxBfOHh"},{"type":"text","value":": DevOps is more about culture and team process than it is about technology, maybe science should be too...","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"key":"jSwWL2wMJt"}],"key":"dbt23AIGvn"}],"key":"labjIMr1F5"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"What is DevOps anyway?","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"key":"Dvyi0oDxkc"}],"identifier":"what-is-devops-anyway","label":"What is DevOps anyway?","html_id":"what-is-devops-anyway","implicit":true,"key":"qBix4ZE8Yb"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This one is going to be hard to define (","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"xg1SV0rCme"},{"type":"link","url":"https://theagileadmin.com/what-is-devops/","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"though here’s one definition","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"QBfvAGYwrZ"}],"urlSource":"https://theagileadmin.com/what-is-devops/","key":"JGkuMzUspB"},{"type":"text","value":"),\nas I’m new to the community as well.\nBut, my take on this is that DevOps is a coming-together of what was once\na bunch of different roles within companies. The process of releasing technology\n(or doing anything really) involves many different steps with different specializations\nneeded at each step. The ‘old way’ of doing things involved teams that’d build\nprototypes, teams that would adapt those prototypes to a company’s infrastructure,\nteams that would maintain and service the “production” deployments, etc. The whole\nprocess was quite slow, partially because of the lack of communication between these\nvery different kinds of groups.","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"GEBao7iqNm"}],"key":"yhVQo99S9s"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":44,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Instead, DevOps attempts to encapsulate this entire process under one moniker. It is\ngenerally recognized that people do have different skills and roles, but they should\nbe working ","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"i5eqbBf5e9"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"together","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"j5G709UsLo"}],"key":"NYqsR0Ve4S"},{"type":"text","value":" in a group to create, mature, and ship new code iteratively\nand as a single continuous process. DevOps is intently focused on “","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"HERE9J1Bmm"},{"type":"link","url":"https://www.versionone.com/agile-101/","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"agile processes","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"ebP5s6zLfG"}],"urlSource":"https://www.versionone.com/agile-101/","key":"IW40s1zARB"},{"type":"text","value":"”,\nand values being quick and lightweight, focusing on metrics like “time between development\nand deployment.” This is only possible with a large focus on team dynamics and\nhow the relationships between people with different skillsets and responsibilities\nshould work with one another effectively. Perhaps unsurprisingly, this is the\nkind of thing that people talk about ","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"EvhMP8n874"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"a lot","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"ryOWTriHIl"}],"key":"IPqdVpw8nH"},{"type":"text","value":" at DevOps conferences (well, at least\nat the one I went to).","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"tJSjCpHGYc"}],"key":"b3N4jdwxJ6"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"DevOpsDays was more about people than tech","position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"key":"kq3fp1FVeQ"}],"identifier":"devopsdays-was-more-about-people-than-tech","label":"DevOpsDays was more about people than tech","html_id":"devopsdays-was-more-about-people-than-tech","implicit":true,"key":"E8tHMbemKp"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":57,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"More than anything else, what struck me was how little emphasis was paid on\nthe technology itself. There are a billion moving parts in the cloud orchestration\nand container technology space, but they got relatively little discussion time at\nthe conference (with the exception of ","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"lVkiE3WNZX"},{"type":"link","url":"https://twitter.com/@jkc137","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Jennelle Crothers","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"qXZceuzj7v"}],"urlSource":"https://twitter.com/@jkc137","key":"fyDAuNJvCh"},{"type":"text","value":"\ntalking about how Microsoft was trying to make its Windows containers super lightweight,\nwhich was pretty neat). In general the only people consistently talking about\nthe greatness of XXX new software/tool/etc were salespeople trying to\nget you to buy their product. Instead, the vast majority of conversations,\ndiscussions, brainstorms, etc were about ","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"YnQ2uyUDag"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"people","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"XBafyCMpxy"}],"key":"xKG8s2lBxk"},{"type":"text","value":" and ","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"Xm6JnXLQFz"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"process","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"lLkI5F4mox"}],"key":"JFpbBnS5DQ"},{"type":"text","value":", not\ntechnology per-se.","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"sOR5Kqqb7l"}],"key":"mMXizhFj3e"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":62,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Obviously, it’s difficult to disentangle the tech from the people when\nyou’re in the tech industry, but it was illustrative to see the\nrelative focus that got placed on the “squishier” questions. For example,\na few that came up pretty frequently:","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"key":"svJhOoGcWF"}],"key":"ktCKo2776A"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":64,"column":1},"end":{"line":69,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":64,"column":1},"end":{"line":64,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How can we disseminate information across a distributed team most effectively?","position":{"start":{"line":64,"column":1},"end":{"line":64,"column":1}},"key":"JYry6MWyf3"}],"key":"Tc61vLXeCY"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How can we create a team culture that welcomes newcomers?","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"key":"J1ZDlYbeKZ"}],"key":"dF4BLZKW8n"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":66,"column":1},"end":{"line":66,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How can we avoid alienating members of the team?","position":{"start":{"line":66,"column":1},"end":{"line":66,"column":1}},"key":"NxlNx4T46Z"}],"key":"npoMNw7CAn"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How can we avoid single points of failure in the team?","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"key":"Oqhhqemju4"}],"key":"w3wyrXiKcU"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":68,"column":1},"end":{"line":69,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How can we do things faster, more efficiently, and more reliably as a team?","position":{"start":{"line":68,"column":1},"end":{"line":68,"column":1}},"key":"xYSMa4UGkp"}],"key":"KXmu6gMtLS"}],"key":"MI1cM3F17o"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"It’s no coincidence that the word “team” was in each of the bullet points above.","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"QIT1u1K8F7"}],"key":"AlxTGVNlkv"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":72,"column":1},"end":{"line":72,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Scientific DevOps?","position":{"start":{"line":72,"column":1},"end":{"line":72,"column":1}},"key":"u7tEffGiIm"}],"identifier":"scientific-devops","label":"Scientific DevOps?","html_id":"scientific-devops","implicit":true,"key":"f2M8byvjMs"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":74,"column":1},"end":{"line":83,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As a member of the scientific / academic community, this is quite interesting\nto me. A whole conference where people talk about creating positive culture and effective\nyeams? Yes please. However, I realize that the incentives and\nproblems associated with DevOps are not the same as those faced by scientists. For\nexample, a big part of DevOps (and SREs more generally) is ensuring that services,\ntools, and sites are reliable and stable over time. You can design tech around this\nidea all you want, but at some point you’ll need a team of people to manage that tech.\nThe DevOps world has seemed to realize that this means the social dynamics of that\nteam are just as important as the technology itself, which is a breath of fresh\nair.","position":{"start":{"line":74,"column":1},"end":{"line":74,"column":1}},"key":"BWqshAFjWL"}],"key":"RCLJ0Zji3B"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":85,"column":1},"end":{"line":90,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I wonder what scientific DevOps would look like. Scientists are theoretically also\noperating in team-based environments (at least, the ones in scientific labs). The\nincentives of reward and recognition are totally misaligned, but it’s still the\ncase that successful teams produce more effective work in general. Perhaps it’s\nworth exploring how the DevOps take on operations and team dynamics ports to\nthe academic scientific community.","position":{"start":{"line":85,"column":1},"end":{"line":85,"column":1}},"key":"innxLUbDYp"}],"key":"Y3IJOF7HO1"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":92,"column":1},"end":{"line":92,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Open and (relatively) diverse culture","position":{"start":{"line":92,"column":1},"end":{"line":92,"column":1}},"key":"tBhdu2FEn2"}],"identifier":"open-and-relatively-diverse-culture","label":"Open and (relatively) diverse culture","html_id":"open-and-relatively-diverse-culture","implicit":true,"key":"WqzVxaJ84z"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":94,"column":1},"end":{"line":102,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A final point that I noticed was that, relative to other tech conferences I’ve\nattended, this one had a general air of positivity and open culture. There were\nall kinds of people there, and while the general makeup of attendees definitely\nstill had a lot of white dudes in it, the room nonetheless never felt like it was\n","position":{"start":{"line":94,"column":1},"end":{"line":94,"column":1}},"key":"AyG70dNk51"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":94,"column":1},"end":{"line":94,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"dominated","position":{"start":{"line":94,"column":1},"end":{"line":94,"column":1}},"key":"tOi716Q3uN"}],"key":"xpwVQKptvE"},{"type":"text","value":" by this group of people. There was also a great culture of supporting\npeople as they were giving talks - some of the speakers were clearly more nervous\nthan others, and the audience did a good job of trying to disarm their anxiety.\nPerhaps this is the kind of culture that comes with a profession that depends on\n(and focuses on) team dynamics and culture.","position":{"start":{"line":94,"column":1},"end":{"line":94,"column":1}},"key":"xIk4eHJnwR"}],"key":"RiJsQoFpv7"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":104,"column":1},"end":{"line":110,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Ultimately, as with any good conference, I left having more questions than answers.\nHow can scientists improve their own team dynamics using principles from the\nDevOps community? How can the open-source community do the same but for distributed team\nworkloads and responsibility? Where is the balance between “solve this with tech” and\n“solve this with people”? How can we encourage more cross-talk between the world of\nscientific research and the world of tech? Either way, it was an interesting and\ninformative experience, and I’m looking forward to learning more about this community.","position":{"start":{"line":104,"column":1},"end":{"line":104,"column":1}},"key":"dEIl3R4RrB"}],"key":"dlO9qcEBAm"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":113,"column":1},"end":{"line":113,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Highlights and takeaways","position":{"start":{"line":113,"column":1},"end":{"line":113,"column":1}},"key":"OWa5rljoWh"}],"identifier":"highlights-and-takeaways","label":"Highlights and takeaways","html_id":"highlights-and-takeaways","implicit":true,"key":"jMal02Nlon"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":114,"column":1},"end":{"line":131,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":114,"column":1},"end":{"line":116,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Amy Nguyen and Adam Barber shared their strategies for taking a ","position":{"start":{"line":114,"column":1},"end":{"line":114,"column":1}},"key":"QfI50mi5dg"},{"type":"link","url":"https://www.devopsdays.org/events/2018-silicon-valley/program/amy-nguyen-adam-barber/","position":{"start":{"line":114,"column":1},"end":{"line":114,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"data-driven approach","position":{"start":{"line":114,"column":1},"end":{"line":114,"column":1}},"key":"LoORQqPcbr"}],"urlSource":"https://www.devopsdays.org/events/2018-silicon-valley/program/amy-nguyen-adam-barber/","key":"Vcned7APID"},{"type":"text","value":" to user interface / experience design.","position":{"start":{"line":114,"column":1},"end":{"line":114,"column":1}},"key":"wwtqckWQLd"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":116,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Always collect data","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"key":"AUd517plRN"}],"key":"GKImmtJwDx"},{"type":"text","value":" from people you design things for.","position":{"start":{"line":115,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"key":"Rb4xirfOIR"}],"key":"zX50M7SYzV"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":116,"column":1},"end":{"line":116,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Put in the legwork to interview and gather diverse perspectives before you build tools.","position":{"start":{"line":116,"column":1},"end":{"line":116,"column":1}},"key":"ISyCRkUOsX"}],"key":"toPMMUEsYA"}],"key":"zgUJgtOQlR"}],"key":"OvaNKitykU"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":117,"column":1},"end":{"line":119,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Fatema Boxwala (","position":{"start":{"line":117,"column":1},"end":{"line":117,"column":1}},"key":"fBM6QRwlLp"},{"type":"link","url":"https://twitter.com/@fatty_box","position":{"start":{"line":117,"column":1},"end":{"line":117,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"fatty_box","position":{"start":{"line":117,"column":1},"end":{"line":117,"column":1}},"key":"KdfWV0V9vX"}],"urlSource":"https://twitter.com/@fatty_box","key":"qJ4ESgBhDq"},{"type":"text","value":") shared her experience as an intern, and gave some pointers for how to create a welcoming and productive environment for intern positions.","position":{"start":{"line":117,"column":1},"end":{"line":117,"column":1}},"key":"DOeWGqsHUc"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":118,"column":1},"end":{"line":119,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":118,"column":1},"end":{"line":118,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Don’t forget that interns have lives too. If they just moved to a new city, help them settle in.","position":{"start":{"line":118,"column":1},"end":{"line":118,"column":1}},"key":"eTRPo4IM5z"}],"key":"aqLqZlcMUa"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":119,"column":1},"end":{"line":119,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Align your intern’s project with something a team member (or yourself) will be actively work on.","position":{"start":{"line":119,"column":1},"end":{"line":119,"column":1}},"key":"iNjurEv1Xy"}],"key":"zzcY6Y0DYn"}],"key":"A4MezDTjM0"}],"key":"BBY5tTAGsj"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":120,"column":1},"end":{"line":122,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Katy Farmer (","position":{"start":{"line":120,"column":1},"end":{"line":120,"column":1}},"key":"ePivkwJszs"},{"type":"link","url":"https://twitter.com/@TheKaterTot","position":{"start":{"line":120,"column":1},"end":{"line":120,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"TheKaterTot","position":{"start":{"line":120,"column":1},"end":{"line":120